{{cite web|url=http://www.buildinghistory.org/mickaston/mickinterview.shtml |title=Mick Aston talks to Radio Times |first=Mick |last=Aston |work=Radio Times Magazine |date=28 August \u2013 3 September 1999 |accessdate=21 March 2011 |via=buildinghistory.org |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6YXVNDQ2T?url=http://www.buildinghistory.org/mickaston/mickinterview.shtml |archivedate=15 May 2015 |url-status=live }}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Telegraph2012\">\n{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/9068025/Mick-Aston-quits-Time-Team-after-producers-hire-former-model-co-presenter.html |title=Mick Aston quits Time Team |date=8 February 2012 |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=21 June 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ZRzTLWvG?url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/9068025/Mick-Aston-quits-Time-Team-after-producers-hire-former-model-co-presenter.html |archivedate=21 June 2015 |url-status=live }}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Telegraph2013\">\n{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/10142000/Professor-Mick-Aston.html |title=Professor Mick Aston |date=25 June 2013 |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=9 September 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6YXTLiqZC?url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/10142000/Professor-Mick-Aston.html |archivedate=15 May 2015 |url-status=live }}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"WesternDailyExpressDecember2012\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.thisissomerset.co.uk/Professor-Mick-Aston-backs-revamp-Somerset-Rural/story-17576353-detail/story.html#axzz2eQRcdxji |title=Professor Mick Aston backs revamp of Somerset Rural Life Museum at Glastonbury |work=Western Daily Press |date=13 December 2012 |accessdate=9 September 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6YXUmcOPF?url=http://www.westerndailypress.co.uk/Professor-Mick-Aston-backs-revamp-Somerset-Rural/story-17576353-detail/story.html#axzz2eQRcdxji |archivedate=15 May 2015 |url-status=dead }}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Williamson2012\">\n{{cite web|last=Williamson |first=Marcus |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/mick-aston-archaeologist-who-found-television-fame-on-time-team-8673645.html |title=Mick Aston: Archaeologist who found television fame on 'Time Team' |date=26 June 2012 |work=The Independent |accessdate=9 September 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6YXV2bFpU?url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/mick-aston-archaeologist-who-found-television-fame-on-time-team-8673645.html |archivedate=15 May 2015 |url-status=live }}\n</ref>\n\n}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last=Aston |first=Mick |title=Mick's Archaeology |year=2000 |publisher=Tempus |isbn=978-0-7524-1480-5 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Lewis |first1=Carenza |last2=Harding |first2=Phil |last3=Aston |first3=Mick |editor-last=Taylor |editor-first=Tim |title=Time Team's Timechester: A Companion to Archaeology |year=2002 |origyear=2000 |publisher=Channel 4 |edition=New |isbn=978-0-7522-6517-9 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Robinson |first1=Tony |last2=Aston |first2=Mick |title=Archaeology is Rubbish: A Beginner's Guide |year=2002 |publisher=Channel 4 Books |isbn=978-0-7522-6519-3 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web |title=Mick's Travels |work=[[Council for British Archaeology|British Archaeology]] |url=http://www.britisharchaeology.org/mickstravels|id=All of Mick Aston's articles in ''British Archaeology'' between September/October 2006 \u2013 July/August 2013}}\n*{{IMDb name|0040074}}\n\n{{Time Team}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aston, Mick}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Bristol]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Birmingham]]\n[[Category:British archaeologists]]\n[[Category:English atheists]]\n[[Category:English anarchists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Society of Antiquaries of London]]\n[[Category:People from Oldbury, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:Archaeologists appearing on Time Team]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name               = Mick Aston\n|image              = MickAston.jpg\n|image_size         = 200px\n|caption=             Mick Aston (left) at the ''[[Time Team]]'' ''Big Roman Dig'' in 2005 with the programme's originator and producer, [[Tim Taylor (producer)|Tim Taylor]]\n|birth_name         = Michael Antony Aston\n|birth_date         = {{birth date|1946|7|1|df=yes}}\n|birth_place        = [[Oldbury, West Midlands|Oldbury]], [[Worcestershire]]<!-- Do not change to West Midlands, Oldbury was part of Worcestershire in 1946 -->, [[England]], [[UK]]\n|death_date         = {{Death date and age|2013|6|24|1946|7|1|df=yes}}\n|death_place        = [[Winscombe]], [[Somerset]], England, UK\n|occupation         = [[Archaeologist]]\n|years_active       = 1988\u20132013\n|known_for          = ''[[Time Team]]'' (1994\u20132013)\n}}\n'''Michael Antony Aston''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FSA|}} (1 July 1946 \u2013 24 June 2013) was an English [[archaeologist]] who specialised in [[Early Middle Ages|Early Medieval]] [[landscape archaeology]]. Over the course of his career, he lectured at both the [[University of Bristol]] and [[University of Oxford]] and published fifteen books on archaeological subjects. A keen populariser of the discipline, Aston was widely known for appearing as the resident academic on the [[Channel 4]] television series ''[[Time Team]]'' from 1994 to 2011.\n\nBorn in [[Oldbury, West Midlands|Oldbury]], [[Worcestershire]], to a working-class family, Aston developed an early interest in archaeology, studying it as a subsidiary to geography at the [[University of Birmingham]]. In 1970, he began his career working for Oxford City and County Museum and there began his work in public outreach by running extramural classes in archaeology and presenting a series on the subject for [[Radio Oxford]]. In 1974, he was appointed the first [[County Archaeologist]] for [[Somerset]], there developing an interest in [[aerial archaeology]] and establishing a reputation as a pioneer in landscape archaeology\u2014a term that he co-invented with [[Trevor Rowley]]\u2014by authoring some of the earliest books on the subject. In 1978 he began lecturing at the University of Oxford and in 1979 became a tutor at the University of Bristol, supplementing these activities by working as an archaeological tour guide in Greece.\n\nIn 1988, Aston teamed up with television producer [[Tim Taylor (producer)|Tim Taylor]] and together they created two shows which focused on bringing archaeology into British popular consciousness. The first was the short-lived ''[[Time Signs]]'' (1991), although this was followed by the more successful ''Time Team'', which was produced for Channel 4 from 1994 to 2013. Aston was responsible for identifying sites for [[Excavation (archaeology)|excavation]] and for selecting specialists to appear on the show, and through the programme became well known to the viewing public for his trademark colourful jumpers and flowing, untidy hairstyle. In 1996 he was appointed to the specially-created post of Professor of Landscape Archaeology at Bristol University, and undertook a ten-year project investigating the manor at [[Shapwick, Somerset]].\nHe retired from his university posts in 2004, but continued working on ''Time Team'' until 2011 and in 2006 commenced writing regular articles for ''[[Council for British Archaeology|British Archaeology]]'' magazine until his death. Although Aston did not believe that he would leave a significant legacy behind him, after his death various archaeologists claimed that he had a major impact in helping to popularise the discipline among the British public.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and education: 1946\u201369===\nAston was born on 1 July 1946 into a working-class family in [[Oldbury, West Midlands|Oldbury]], [[Worcestershire]]<!-- Do not change to West Midlands, Oldbury was part of Worcestershire in 1946 -->, to cabinet-maker Harold Aston and his wife Gladys.{{r|Dyer2013}}{{r|Telegraph2013}} He developed an early interest in archaeology, although teachers at [[Langley High School, Oldbury|Oldbury Grammar School]] attempted to dissuade him from pursuing it.{{r|Telegraph2013}}{{sfnp|Aston|2000|p=13}} His father gave him two books on archaeology as a Christmas present, and he subsequently spent much time visiting archaeological sites, sometimes [[truancy|playing truant]] to do so.{{sfnp|Aston|2000|p=11}}{{r|Hilts2013}} The first of his family to attend university, Aston studied geography at the [[University of Birmingham]], albeit with a subsidiary in archaeology, graduating in 1967.{{r|Telegraph2013}}{{sfnp|Aston|2000|p=14}}{{r|PriorHorton}}{{r|BBC2013}} He taught himself more about archaeology by enrolling in various [[excavation (archaeology)|excavations]],{{r|Dyer2013}}{{sfnp|Aston|2000|p=13}}{{r|Hilts2013}} and was influenced by such figures as his thesis supervisor Harry Thorpe, as well as the geographer Trevor Rowley and archaeologists [[Philip Rahtz]] and Philip Barker.{{r|Dyer2013}}{{sfnp|Aston|2000|pp=14\u201316}} His dissertation was on the development of settlement in the West [[Penwith]] peninsula.{{sfnp|Aston|2000|p=51}}\n\n===Early career: 1970\u201387===\nAston first gained full-time employment in 1970, working as a field officer at the Oxford City and County Museum in [[Oxfordshire]]. For a time living in a tent, he worked on the [[sites and monuments record]] and taught several extramural classes while based at the museum.{{r|Dyer2013}}{{r|Telegraph2013}}{{r|Archaeology2013}} This extramural teaching fitted closely with Aston's staunch belief that archaeology should be open to all who were interested in it.{{r|PriorHorton}} As part of this devotion to public outreach, he presented a radio series on archaeology that was broadcast on [[Radio Oxford]].{{r|Archaeology2013}}{{sfnp|Aston|2000|p=26}} In 1974 he moved to [[Taunton]] to become the first [[County Archaeologist]] for [[Somerset]], where he set up a new site record and oversaw the excavation of sites revealed by the construction of the [[M5 motorway]]. Again he also taught extramural adult education classes, this time for the [[University of Bristol]].{{r|Dyer2013}}{{r|Telegraph2013}}{{r|Archaeology2013}}{{sfnp|Aston|2000|pp=18\u201319}} It was here that he developed a passion for [[aerial archaeology]], and would often charter private planes in order to undertake aerial photography.{{r|PriorHorton}}{{sfnp|Aston|2000|p=44}} Becoming a pioneer of landscape archaeology, along with Trevor Rowley he was responsible for coining the term in their 1974 book, ''Landscape Archaeology''.{{r|Dyer2013}}{{r|PriorHorton}}{{r|Gerrard}} With archaeologist James Bond he authored ''The Landscape of Towns'' (1976), in which he extended his use of landscape archaeology to urban areas.{{r|Dyer2013}} Recognising his contribution to the discipline, in 1976, he was elected a Fellow of the [[Society of Antiquaries of London]].{{r|Telegraph2013}}\n\nTiring of his position as county archaeologist, finding it \"too safe, pensionable and superannuable\", in 1978 he returned to Oxfordshire to take up a temporary position as a tutor in archaeology and local studies at [[Oxford University]]'s External Studies Department.{{r|Dyer2013}}{{r|Telegraph2013}}{{r|Archaeology2013}}{{sfnp|Aston|2000|pp=19\u201320}} That year he co-ran his first study tour to Greece with Peter Hardy; he would continue to run these annually for a number of years, most often visiting [[Santorini]].{{sfnp|Aston|2000|p=52}} In 1979 he returned to the West Country as tutor in archaeology at the [[University of Bristol]]'s Extra-Mural Department,{{r|Telegraph2013}}{{r|BBC2013}}{{sfnp|Aston|2000|p=20}} through which he organised weekend and evening courses throughout the region, introducing thousands of interested people to archaeology.{{r|PriorHorton}} During this period he also authored ''Interpreting the Landscape'' (1985).{{r|Dyer2013}}\n\n===Founding ''Time Team'': 1988\u201395===\n[[File:TimeTeam2007.jpg|thumb|right|Aston (centre) with presenter Sir [[Tony Robinson]] (left) and Roman expert [[Guy de la B\u00e9doy\u00e8re]] (right) during a ''Time Team'' dig]]\n\nIn June 1988 the producer [[Tim Taylor (producer)|Tim Taylor]] invited Aston to work on a new four-episode television series for [[Channel 4]] called ''[[Time Signs]]'', broadcast in June and July 1991. The series focused on the historical development of the area about to be flooded by the [[Roadford Lake|Roadford Reservoir]] in [[Devon]], making heavy use of archaeological data. Aston brought archaeologist [[Phil Harding (archaeologist)|Phil Harding]] into the project in order to explain techniques of [[experimental archaeology]] to the audience.{{r|PriorHorton}}{{sfnp|Aston|2000|p=27}} Meanwhile, in August 1989, Aston was promoted to the position of [[Reader (academic rank)|Reader]] in Landscape Archaeology at Bristol University.{{r|PriorHorton}}{{sfnp|Aston|2000|p=23}} He also continued to write on the subject, authoring the book ''Monasteries'' (1993);{{r|Dyer2013}} he had initially planned to title the volume ''Monasteries in the Landscape'' but his publisher, [[Batsford]], had insisted on the shorter title.{{sfnp|Aston|2000|p=110}}\n\nAston and Taylor subsequently decided to work together on a new archaeological television series, devising the format for ''[[Time Team]]''. Whilst Taylor organised the film production side of the project with Channel 4, Aston located suitable sites to excavate, and gathered together a team of specialists to appear on the show, among them field archaeologists Harding and [[Carenza Lewis]], artist [[Victor Ambrus]], and historian [[Robin Bush (historian)|Robin Bush]]. He knew the actor and television presenter [[Tony Robinson]] after they had met on an archaeological course in [[Greece]], and successfully requested that he present the show.{{sfnp|Aston|2000|pp=28\u201330}} From an early stage, they had agreed that every episode would feature a practical process or a re-enactment alongside the field archaeology.{{sfnp|Aston|2000|p=79}}\n\n''Time Team'' was first broadcast in 1994, and would attract around four million viewers per episode, with Aston becoming \"an icon to the viewing public.\"{{r|PriorHorton}} Writing in ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[Christopher Dyer]] noted that Aston's \"unkempt hair and beard, multicoloured sweaters and [[Black Country]] accent made him instantly recognisable\" to the British public, describing him as \"a popular success\" who had attracted \"a large public following\".{{r|Dyer2013}} Aston acted as chief archaeological adviser to the programme until the end of series nineteen, appearing in almost every episode,{{r|PriorHorton}}{{r|BBC2013}} although he would later comment that when it first started he had no idea it would continue for so long.{{r|Eggington}} Aston enjoyed working with the ''Time Team'' crew, commenting that they were \"a great gang&nbsp;... There are some real party people.\"{{r|Hilts2013}}\n\nAston saw ''Time Team'' as an extension of his work as an extramural tutor, telling a 2013 interviewer that it was \"a way of reaching 3 million people rather than 30 people in the village hall.\"{{r|Hilts2013}} Commenting on the popularity of ''Time Team'', and its role in exposing the British public to archaeology, in a 2010 interview Aston remarked that \"My motive was to get as many people as possible interested in archaeology, because we [in the profession] all enjoy it and think it interesting. That was my personal aim&nbsp;... and on that basis I think it is a success.\"{{r|Aston2010}} ''Time Team'' encouraged wider public interest in archaeology and led to increasing numbers of students applying to study archaeological courses at British universities,{{r|PriorHorton}} while subscriptions to ''Current Archaeology'' magazine quadrupled to 18,000 in the show's first five years.{{sfnp|Aston|2000|p=40}} In autumn 1998, Channel 4 started a ''Time Team'' fan club, which had 16,000 members within a few months,{{sfnp|Aston|2000|p=40}} while Aston became a supporter of the [[Council for British Archaeology]]'s Young Archaeologists' Club (YAC), and with Harding gave regular talks to YAC branches.{{sfnp|Aston|2000|p=42}} Aston found himself giving up to 20 public lectures a year on the subject of ''Time Team'', describing the public feedback as \"embarrassingly encouraging\".{{sfnp|Aston|2000|p=42}}\n\n===Professorship: 1996\u20132011===\nIn 1996, Aston was appointed to the position of Professor of Landscape Archaeology at Bristol University's Department of Continuing Education, a post designed explicitly for him.{{r|PriorHorton}}{{r|BBC2013}} In 1998 the post was moved to the Centre for the Historic Environment within the Department of Archaeology.{{r|PriorHorton}} He would subsequently be instrumental in setting up the master's degree in archaeology and screen media at the department.{{r|Bailey}} By 1996, Aston was feeling \"a bit frustrated\" with ''Time Team'', primarily because he was always \"number two\" to Robinson.{{sfnp|Aston|2000|p=36}} He proceeded to present his own six-episode series, ''[[Time Traveller (1997 series)|Time Traveller]]'', in which he explored various archaeological sites in the counties around Bristol. It was broadcast on [[ITV Wales & West|HTV]] over July and August 1997, and gained the largest local audiences for its time slot.{{sfnp|Aston|2000|pp=37\u201339}}\n\nThe archaeology students of [[University of Winchester|King Alfred's College, Winchester]] also participated in a 10-year project led by Aston to investigate the manor of [[Shapwick, Somerset|Shapwick]] in [[Somerset]].{{r|BBC2013}}{{r|Archaeology2013}} It became the \"type site for the study of the development of medieval villages\".{{r|PriorHorton}} Aston published the results of the project in ''The Shapwick Project, Somerset: A Rural Landscape Explored'' (2007), co-written with Christopher Gerrard, and this was followed by a more popular account of the project, ''Interpreting the English Village'', in 2013.{{r|Telegraph2013}}{{r|PriorHorton}}\n\nAlongside his academic publications, Aston wrote two books on archaeology for a more general audience, both of which were published by [[Channel 4 Books]] as a spin-off from the ''Time Team'' television series. The first of these was ''Time Team's Timechester: A Companion to Archaeology'', co-written with [[Carenza Lewis]] and [[Phil Harding (archaeologist)|Phil Harding]] and first published in 2000. Based around the fictional British town of Timechester, the book looks at how the settlement would have progressed from the [[Palaeolithic]] through to the modern day, and examines the remains that each period would have left behind in the archaeological record.{{sfnp|Lewis|Harding|Aston|2002|p=}} This was followed in 2002 by ''Archaeology is Rubbish: A Beginner's Guide'', which Aston co-wrote with [[Tony Robinson]] and dedicated to Harding. ''Archaeology is Rubbish'' describes a fictional excavation site in an ordinary suburban back garden, and discusses the evidence from different archaeological periods, the field methods and techniques used by the excavators, and the legal proceedings and problems that archaeologists in Britain face.{{sfnp|Robinson|Aston|2002|p=}}\n\nAston retired from Bristol University in 2004, subsequently becoming Professor Emeritus.{{r|PriorHorton}}{{r|BBC2013}}{{r|Archaeology2013}} He was also appointed an Honorary Visiting Professor at the [[University of Exeter]], [[University of Durham]], and the [[University of Worcester]].{{r|Telegraph2013}}{{r|PriorHorton}}{{r|BBC2013}} That year, the [[University of Winchester]] awarded him an [[honorary degree|honorary]] [[Doctor of Letters]].{{r|PriorHorton}} In 2006 Aston began writing a regular column, \"Mick's Travels\", for the bimonthly journal ''British Archaeology'', the publication of the [[Council for British Archaeology]].{{r|PriorHorton}}{{r|Articles}} In 2007, Worcester University awarded Aston an honorary doctorate; that same year a number of his colleagues released a ''[[festschrift]]'' in his honour entitled ''People and Places: Essays in Honour of Michael Aston''.{{r|PriorHorton}}\n\n===Final years: 2012\u201313===\nIn February 2012 it was reported that Aston had left ''Time Team''. He explained his position to the ''[[Western Daily Press]]'', stating that the show's producers had made a number of changes to the series without consulting him, and that in the process ''Time Team'' had been \"[[dumbing down|dumbed down]]\", something he considered bad for archaeology. He was annoyed that a number of archaeologists\u2014including surveyor [[Stewart Ainsworth]], small finds specialist [[Helen Geake]] and illustrator [[Victor Ambrus]]\u2014had seen their roles diminished while a new co-presenter, [[Mary-Ann Ochota]] (a former model with a bachelor's degree in archaeology and anthropology), had been introduced, and that as a result the episodes now contained \"a lot of faffing about.\"{{r|Telegraph2013}}{{r|Aston2012}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.westerndailypress.co.uk/Professor-Mick-Aston-quits-Time-Team-dumbing-row/story-15177582-detail/story.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414220332/http://www.westerndailypress.co.uk/Professor-Mick-Aston-quits-Time-Team-dumbing-row/story-15177582-detail/story.html| title=Professor Mick Aston quits Time Team over 'dumbing down' row|publisher=Western Daily Press | date= 9 Feb 2012| access-date=9 Apr 2020| archive-date=14 Apr 2014}}</ref> In an interview with the magazine ''British Archaeology'' Aston said: \"The time had come to leave. I never made any money out of it, but a lot of my soul went into it. I feel really, really angry about it.\"{{r|Telegraph2012}}\n\n{{Quote box\n| width = 246px\n| align = left\n| quote = \"I've decided to quit Time Team because Channel 4 decided to alter the format. There is a lot less archaeological content and a lot more pratting about. I was the archaeological consultant but they decided to get rid of half the archaeological team, without consulting me. I think it has dumbed down.\"\n| salign = right\n| source = \u2014 Aston, 2012{{r|Aston2012}}\n}}\n\nIn July, 2012, Aston received a lifetime achievement award at the British Archaeological Awards, with Bristol University's Professor Mark Horton praising him for making \"the past accessible to all\".{{r|Telegraph2013}}{{r|BBC2013}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.archaeology.co.uk/articles/news/lifetime-achievement-award-for-mick-aston.htm| title=Lifetime achievement award for Mick Aston|access-date=9 Apr 2020}}</ref> In October, Channel 4 announced that the twentieth series of ''Time Team'' would be its last as the show was being axed.{{r|BBC2013}} In December Aston signed a petition advocating his support for the revamp of the [[Somerset Rural Life Museum]] in [[Glastonbury]], which was then seeking financial backers.{{r|WesternDailyExpressDecember2012}}\n\nOn 24 June 2013 it was announced that Aston had died unexpectedly of a [[intracerebral hemorrhage|brain haemorrhage]] at his home in Somerset.<ref>[https://doi.org/10.1093/ref:odnb/106884 Oxford Dictionary of National Biography: Aston, Michael Antony]</ref>{{r|PriorHorton}} He had been due to receive an honorary doctorate in [[University College Dublin]] that September.\nRalph Lee, head of Channel 4's factual programming, announced that they had been \"terribly saddened\" by the news, and that they were planning a \"tribute night\" to Aston consisting of ''Time Team'' episodes to be screened on [[More4]] on 13 July.{{r|Eames}}{{Clear}}\n\n==Selected works==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|+\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Co-author(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Publisher\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | ISBN\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Landscape Archaeology: An Introduction to Fieldwork Techniques on Post-Roman Landscapes''\n| 1974\n| {{sortname|Trevor |Rowley|nolink=1}}\n| David and Charles\n| 978-0715366707\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sort|''Landscape of Towns, The''|''The Landscape of Towns''}}\n| 1976, 2000 (revised ed.)\n| {{sortname|James |Bond|nolink=1}}\n| Littlehampton Book Services\n| 978-0460041942\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Interpreting the Landscape: Landscape Archaeology in Local Studies''\n| 1985\n| \u2013\n| Routledge\n| 978-0713436501\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Aspects of the Medieval Landscape of Somerset''\n| 1988\n| \u2013\n| Somerset County Council\n| 0-86183-129-2\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sort|''Rural Settlements of Medieval England, The''|''The Rural Settlements of Medieval England: Studies Dedicated to Maurice Beresford and John Hurst''}}\n| 1989\n| {{sortname|David |Austen|nolink=1}}, Christopher Dyer\n| Basil Blackwell\n| 978-0631159032\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Monasteries''<br>''Monasteries in the Landscape'' (revised. ed.)\n| 1993, 2000 (revised. ed.)\n| \u2013\n| Batsford<br>The History Press (rev.)\n| 978-0713467093<br>978-0752414911 (rev.)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sort|''Medieval Landscape of Wessex, The''|''The Medieval Landscape of Wessex''}}\n| 1994\n| {{sortname|Carenza |Lewis|nolink=1}}\n| Oxbow\n| 978-0946897780\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sort|''Atlas of Archaeology, The''|''The Atlas of Archaeology''}}\n| 1998\n| {{sortname|Tim |Taylor|nolink=1}}\n| Dorling Kindersley\n| 978-0751303209\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Mick's Archaeology''\n| 2000, 2002 (revised ed.)\n| \u2013\n| Tempus<br>The History Press (rev)\n| 978-0752414805\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Time Team's Timechester''\n| 2000\n| {{sortname|Carenza |Lewis|nolink=1}}, Phil Harding, and Tim Taylor\n| Channel 4\n| 978-0752272184\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Monastic Archaeology: Papers on the Study of Medieval Monasteries''\n| 2001\n| {{sortname|Graham |Keevill|nolink=1}}, Teresa Hall\n| Oxbow\n| 978-1842170298\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Archaeology is Rubbish: A Beginner's Guide''\n| 2002\n| {{sortname|Tony |Robinson|nolink=1}}\n| Channel 4\n| 978-0752265193\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Interpreting the Landscape from the Air''\n| 2002\n| \u2013\n| NPI Media Group\n| 978-0752425207\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sort|''Shapwick Project, Somerset, The''|''The Shapwick Project, Somerset: A Rural Landscape Explored''}}\n| 2007\n| {{sortname|Chris |Gerrard|nolink=1}}\n| Maney\n| 978-1905981861\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Interpreting the English Village: Landscape and Community at Shapwick, Somerset''\n| 2013\n| {{sortname|Chris |Gerrard|nolink=1}}\n| Windgather Press\n| 978-1905119455\n|-\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\n{{Quote box\n| width = 246px\n| align = right\n| quote = \"Mick Aston was a great British eccentric; an atheist whose life's work was medieval monasticism, an anarchist who for many decades loyally fulfilled the labyrinthine requirements of his university and British television, and a grumpy old curmudgeon with the kindest of hearts and a great capacity for friendship&nbsp;... His mission was sharing his passion for archaeology with ordinary people rather than keeping its secrets locked away behind the walls of Britain's universities.\"\n| salign = right\n| source = \u2014 Tony Robinson, 2013{{r|Eames}}\n}}\n\nAston was known for his \"unfailing commitment and integrity\", with his life being dominated by \"old-fashioned idealism and loyalty\".{{r|Bailey}} He was a [[vegetarianism|vegetarian]] and a [[naturist]],{{r|Telegraph2013}}{{r|Archaeology2013}} as well as an [[anarchism|anarchist]] and an [[atheism|atheist]].{{r|Eames}}{{r|Williamson2012}} Describing himself as \"a keen European\",{{sfnp|Aston|2000|p=104}} a friend of his noted that he \"railed against right wing politics, reserving special venom for [[Margaret Thatcher]], and fought against all manner of authority, including university paperwork, and most especially if it came in a uniform.\"{{r|Gerrard}}\n\nHis hobbies included gardening, pottery, astronomy, listening to classical music and cooking.{{r|Gerrard}}{{r|RadioTimes}}{{r|Blessings}} He supported a number of charities and other causes, including [[Greenpeace]], the [[Woodland Trust]], [[Oxfam]] and [[Sightsavers International]].{{r|GoodCauses}} He liked to live a private, hermit-like life, and once commented that \"For some of the time I feel I could be a monk\" but that he \"couldn't cope with the celibacy.\"{{r|Archaeology2013}}{{sfnp|Aston|2000|p=100}} A self-described \"solitary person\", he found it somewhat annoying being a television celebrity and being recognised by members of the public.{{r|Eggington}}{{r|Blessings}}\n\nAston had a son, James, and a stepdaughter, Kathryn, both children of his former partner Carinne Allinson, with whom he broke up in 1998.{{r|Dyer2013}}{{r|Telegraph2013}}{{r|BBC2013}} He later entered into a relationship with landscape historian Teresa Hall, who survived him on his death.{{r|Dyer2013}} He lived in what he called \"a rather grotty '60s bungalow\" in [[Somerset]].{{r|Telegraph2013}}{{r|RadioTimes}} The reporter Steve Eggington visited Aston's home in 2008, where he noted that it was filled with \"a labyrinth of books and maps, seemingly with different projects at different stages in each room.\"{{r|Eggington}}\n\nAston commented that throughout his life he suffered from poor health; he was afflicted with [[aspergillosis]] from the early 1980s,{{r|Telegraph2013}}{{r|Aston2010}} and was also [[asthma]]tic.{{r|RadioTimes}} He suffered a [[brain haemorrhage]] in March 2003, and was hospitalised for two weeks. The experience sent him into depression for eighteen months, during which time he read the autobiography of actress [[Jane Lapotaire]], who had gone through the same experience, something which he believed aided his recovery more than anything else.{{r|Telegraph2013}}{{r|Aston2010}}{{r|Eggington}}\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Mick Aston and Tony Robinson, Waltham Fields, 2000.jpg|thumb|Mick Aston and Tony Robinson, ''Time Team'' series 8 shoot at Waltham Fields, Whittington, Gloucestershire, England, 2000]]\n\nAston did not believe that he would leave a significant legacy behind him.{{r|Hilts2013}} He commented that this was the case because Britain's archaeological community had failed to develop the work that he had done with ''Time Team'' and with extramural teaching, and that all the public outreach he had accomplished would die with him.{{r|Hilts2013}} He felt that there was no \"celebrity archaeologist\" to replace him, and ultimately felt that the situation in British archaeology made him \"angry and sad.\"{{r|Hilts2013}}\n\nIn ''British Archaeology'' magazine, Aston was described as \"the [[Mortimer Wheeler]] of our times\" because, despite strong differences between their personalities, both had done much to bring archaeology to the British public.{{r|Archaeology2013}} It went on to note that Aston reminded archaeologists that \"their job is to do archaeology, and if that was an archaeology that meant nothing to ordinary people, there was no point in it\u2014and government would be among the first to notice.\"{{r|Archaeology2013}} Two of Aston's colleagues from Bristol University, Stuart Prior and Mark Horton, commented that \"Mick brought archaeology into the living rooms of half the nation, and left a legacy that will shape the discipline for decades to come.\"{{r|PriorHorton}} Writing for the website of ''[[Antiquity (journal)|Antiquity]]'', [[Christopher Gerrard]] described him as \"perhaps the best-known face in British archaeology\", adding that \"in so many different areas of medieval archaeology his legacy will live on.\"{{r|Gerrard}} Emma McFarnon described Aston as \"Somerset's premier archaeologist\" in her obituary on the This is Somerset website.{{r|McFarnon}}\n\nFollowing Aston's death, former colleague [[Francis Pryor]] noted that Aston was a \"remarkable archaeologist who could really dig\", being a \"warm, loving, nice man.\"{{r|BBC2013}} Another colleague, [[Phil Harding (archaeologist)|Phil Harding]], commented on Aston's \"incredible knowledge\" and \"effortless way of making archaeology accessible to people.\"{{r|BBC2013}} Tony Robinson wrote of him: \"Mick was a real child of the '60s and a bit of a rebel, but he was also a series of contradictions. He was one of the best academic archaeologists in the country, yet his real love was teaching ordinary people. He was the grumpiest old Black Country curmudgeon you could imagine, but he had a heart of absolute gold.\"<ref>Tony Robinson, \"Mick Aston: 1946-2013\", ''Radio Times'', 6\u201312 July 2013, p.143</ref> He also noted that \"archaeology is now a subject that tens of thousands of people enjoy and value, and this is almost solely down to him.\"{{r|Eames}} Ralph Lee, head of Channel 4's factual programming, described Aston as a \"brilliant communicator\" who helped make archaeology \"so popular\" in the UK.{{r|BBC2013}}\n\n===Sculpture at Bristol University===\nA bronze bust of Mick Aston was unveiled at the [[University of Bristol]] on 26 March 2018.<ref name=MA_Bust>{{cite web| title=Bronze bust unveiled of Time Team presenter and university archaeology professor| url=https://www.bristol.ac.uk/news/2018/march/mick-aston-bust.html| publisher=University of Bristol| date=26 March 2018| access-date=5 April 2018}}</ref> The bust, created by sculptor Alex Peter, has been installed at the Department of Anthropology and Archaeology in a ceremony that his former partner Teresa Hall and colleagues attended. Aston worked at the University for more than 25 years and was a familiar face on Time Team for 19 years. Sculptor Alex Peter said: \"To acknowledge Aston for his academic contributions is a beautiful and a very meaningful thing.\"<ref name=MA_Bust/> Fellow archaeologist [[Mark Horton (archaeologist)|Mark Horton]] stated: \"Mick was such an amazing archaeologist in so many different ways.\" The public can view the bust by contacting the School of Arts.<ref name=MA_Bust/>\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Archaeology2013\">\n{{cite news |title=A Life in Archaeology: Michael Antony Aston |year=2013 |author=''British Archaeology'' |journal=British Archaeology |number=132 |pages=16\u201317}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Articles\">\n{{cite web|url=http://www.buildinghistory.org/mickaston/micksarticles.shtml |title=Selected Articles by Mick Aston |last=Aston |first=Mick |publisher=Mick Aston |accessdate=9 September 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6YXU2c03v?url=http://www.buildinghistory.org/mickaston/micksarticles.shtml |archivedate=15 May 2015 |url-status=live }}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Aston2010\">\n{{cite journal|title=Jersey: a defended island |author=Aston, Mick |date=September\u2013October 2010 |journal=British Archaeology |pages=46\u201347 |volume=104}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Aston2012\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.thisissomerset.co.uk/Professor-Mick-Aston-quit-Time-Team-danger-losing/story-15214966-detail/story.html#axzz2XAroGZ5v |title=Professor Mick Aston: Why I quit Time Team, and the danger of losing touch with our history |last=Aston |first=Mick |newspaper=Western Daily Press |date=13 February 2012 |accessdate=9 September 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6YXUZGVMm?url=http://www.westerndailypress.co.uk/Professor-Mick-Aston-quit-Time-Team-danger-losing/story-15214966-detail/story.html#axzz2XAroGZ5v |archivedate=15 May 2015 |url-status=dead }}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Bailey\">\n{{cite news |title=Greg Bailey on broadcasting |last=Bailey |first=Greg |year=2013 |journal=British Archaeology |number=132 |p=14}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BBC2013\">\n{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-23041568 |title=Mick Aston, ex-Time Team expert, dies aged 66 |author=BBC News |date=25 June 2013 |work=BBC News |accessdate=9 September 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6YXTml7BR?url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-23041568 |archivedate=15 May 2015 |url-status=live }}\n</ref>\n\n<ref